      <hedline>
        <hl1>In 50 States</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Martha H Peak letter on W D Wetherell's June 4 travel article holds aficionados would not dart across borders or visit airports to say they visited certain US states (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: W. D. Wetherell describes approvingly the traveler's quickie stop under the ''Welcome to'' sign. True cognoscenti of the sport know that to count a state you have to experience it, not just leave tread marks on a corner of it.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: W. D. Wetherell describes approvingly the traveler's quickie stop under the ''Welcome to'' sign. True cognoscenti of the sport know that to count a state you have to experience it, not just leave tread marks on a corner of it.</p>
        <p>Airport visits are anathema as well. Aficionados allow only one exception to the ''no quickie visit'' rule:  a trip to Four Corners will bag Colorado, New Mexico, Arizona and Utah, but only if the visitor places an arm or leg in each of the appropriate states and holds the position long enough for the requisite photo. Under these rules, I have 45 states so far and my husband has 34.</p>
        <p>MARTHA H. PEAK  Chicago</p>
      </block>
